{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490946"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:24:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:24:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"779"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/779"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.11,0.66,0.13,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109765"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/779"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92164"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"3446"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37223"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109765"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-week history of intermittent burning pain in his upper abdomen. The pain starts about one hour after a meal and he has been taking an antacid preparation to relieve his symptoms. He has a medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidaemia, for which he takes perindopril and simvastatin. He is a smoker with a 25 pack-year history and drinks two cans of beer per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 84/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A urea breath test is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial plan of treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lifestyle modification","Commence proton pump inhibitor, treat H. pylori if ongoing symptoms at next review","Amoxicillin, clarithromycin and esomeprazole for seven days","Metronidazole, clarithromycin and esomeprazole for seven days","Refer for gastroscopy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of peptic ulcer disease and positive \u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E (\u003Cem\u003EH. pylori) \u003C/em\u003Etesting. \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E is a gram-negative bacterium that colonizes the gastric mucosa, inducing inflammation and disrupting the protective mucus layer. This can progress to peptic ulcer disease, and in some cases, gastric cancer. The bacterium is also associated with gastric mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) lymphoma. Therefore, it is recommended that patients who are diagnosed with \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori \u003C/em\u003Eare offered eradication treatment. Follow-up testing to confirm \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori \u003C/em\u003Eeradication should be performed at least four weeks after completion of therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate first-line treatment is \u003Cstrong\u003Eamoxicillin, clarithromycin and esomeprazole for seven days\u003C/strong\u003E. This triple therapy regimen is the current standard first-line treatment option for \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori \u003C/em\u003Eeradication in Australia. It combines two antibiotics with a proton pump inhibitor to effectively eliminate the bacteria and reduce stomach acid production. Statins can interact with macrolide antibiotics and in this particular case, the patient should stop his simvastatin whilst he is taking the clarithromycin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole, clarithromycin and esomeprazole for seven days\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative triple therapy regimen which is recommended in cases of penicillin allergy. However, amoxicillin-based regimens are generally preferred as first-line treatment due to lower rates of antibiotic resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELifestyle modification\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient for managing this patient\u0027s symptoms and addressing the underlying \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E infection. While reducing alcohol intake and smoking cessation are important as these factors can contribute to peptic ulcer disease and interfere with healing, they alone do not address the bacterial infection or facilitate effective ulcer healing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option to \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommence proton pump inhibitor (PPI), treat \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E if ongoing symptoms at next review\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate. While a PPI may improve his symptoms and aid peptic ulcer healing if present, \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori \u003C/em\u003Eeradication should be initiated when detected to prevent ongoing complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary at this stage. Gastroscopy is typically reserved for patients with alarm symptoms (such as unexplained weight loss, dysphagia, or gastrointestinal bleeding) or those who fail initial \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori \u003C/em\u003Etreatment. Gastroscopy allows direct visualization of the gastric mucosa, biopsy for histological examination, and \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E culture with antibiotic sensitivity testing. This patient has no alarm symptoms and has not yet undergone eradication therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Triple therapy with amoxicillin, clarithromycin, and a proton pump inhibitor for seven days is the first-line treatment option for H. pylori infection in patients with suspected peptic ulcer disease.","Gastroscopy is indicated in patients with alarm symptoms or those who fail initial treatment."],"references":["Yaxley J, Chakravarty B. Helicobacter pylori eradication - an update on the latest therapies. Aust Fam Physician. 2014 May;43(5):301-5. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2014/may/helicobacter-pylori-eradication","Safavi M, Sabourian R, Foroumadi A. Treatment of Helicobacter pylori infection: Current and future insights. World J Clin Cases. 2016 Jan 16;4(1):5-19. doi: 10.12998/wjcc.v4.i1.5. PMID: 26798626; PMCID: PMC4714294. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26798626/","Aumpan N, Mahachai V, Vilaichone RK. Management of Helicobacter pylori infection. JGH Open. 2022 Nov 21;7(1):3-15. doi: 10.1002/jgh3.12843. PMID: 36660052; PMCID: PMC9840198. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9840198/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92164"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"779"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92164"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-26T11:16:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-26T11:19:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"779"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109765"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11